{
  "answer": "**The work is *Old English Elegies* (Chapter 16, \"Wraetlic is þes wealstan\" — commonly known as \"The Ruin\").**[^1]\n\nThis Old English poem contemplates the ruins of a once-great (Roman) city, describing its massive walls as the \"work of giants,\" with \"roofs [...] toppled, towers in ruin, the barred gate plundered.\"[^2] It then specifically evokes the city's elaborate bath-houses:\n\n> Stone courts stood; a stream threw up heat  \n> in a wide surge; a wall enclosed all  \n> within its bright embrace, where the baths were,  \n> hot at their heart. That was a welcome thing.  \n> They let pour then over the grey stone  \n> hot streams [...]  \n> [...] until the round pool grew hot [...][^3]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 16](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-dfdbda).  \n(The quoted translation by Thothica includes ellipses where the fragmentary manuscript is damaged or obscure.)",
